Chad Woolley wrote:

&gt;Actually, I wasn&#39;t meaning asserts outside your tests. I meant in your 
&gt;failing test, before and after the invocation of the Class Under Test. 
&gt;However, use whatever works - and the assert approach may not work at all.
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
Good, because that won&#39;t work.  The production code gets used in many 
paths, and I decided the asserts in it would be to &quot;generic&quot; to help.

&gt;Also, I&#39;ll mention another idea, although it may be anathema to this 
&gt;list.  If you can somehow DETECT the failure, put a breakpoint in your 
&gt;application (System.in or something to that effect), and then fire up 
&gt;your debugger and inspect the state of everything.
&gt;
&gt;I know that many people on this list (and Dave Astel&#39;s in his fine book) 
&gt;say you shouldn&#39;t need the debugger if you TDD intensively enough.  I 
&gt;myself am unfortunately not to that level yet, and I often find it 
&gt;useful to fire up the debugger.
&gt;
&gt;Whatever approach you use, I think the general idea is to gradually 
&gt;narrow down the scope of the unknown failure until you can see what is 
&gt;the root cause.
&gt;
&gt;  
&gt;
That&#39;s certainly the cause.  The problem is that I only see it once a 
day or so, so narrowing it down may take a while.  I was hoping 
(originally) that runing it &quot;a lot&quot;, under &quot;random conditions&quot; might 
make it show itself more than once a day.


&gt;Hope this helps,
&gt;Chad
&gt;
&gt;David Corbin wrote:
&gt;  
&gt;
&gt;&gt;Prefectly reasonable suggestion.  I&#39;ll give it a try. For some reason, I 
&gt;&gt;don&#39;t think of asserts outside my tests.  (I&#39;m don&#39;t like the clutter).
